Political Leaning in Correlation with COVID-19 Outcomes

Ben Leland, Krithik Duraisamy, Selma Link, Valerie Lam

11/13/22

Summary

The use of this report is to inform those of the correlation between political leaning and containment and neutralization of the COVID-19 virus. Since its discovery in late 2019, COVID-19 has been a growing issue and evaluating the success of efforts to contain it is an important issue. To identify similarities between politics and neutralization efforts multiple points of data will be evaluated. The data being: election results, vaccine, hesitancy, death counts, and mask use. To begin, the election held in 2020 contained vital information for the political leanings of the public. The votes are as such: Donald Trump had 74,218,999 votes, whereas Joe Biden had 81,264,648 votes. This states that majority of the US population was leaning towards democrat and higher restrictions on protection against COVID-19. From this, the average percentage of people who actually wore masks can be correlated to political leaning. 0.08 percent of people did not choose to wear a mask outdoors, 0.12 percent of people sometimes chose to wear a mask, and 0.51 percent of people always chose to wear a mask. From this data it can be deduced that 51% of the population chose to wear a mask outdoors correlating to the data that democrats were majority of that population at the time. In contrast, those who chose to not wear masks as often fell ill quicker and easier. The average number of deaths per county in the US from January 1, 2020 to October 22, 2022 was 392. An idea can be construed that death counts can be correlated to mask usage further proven by political leaning and policies made between 2020 and 2022. Further evidence is needed to prove this and will be produced in visual displays.

The table encompasses all of the data used to create the data visualizations. The table is aggregated by state which summarizes the different values for each state in regards to COVID outcomes and effects.

Chart 1

The bar chart above illustrates the amount of deaths per 100,000 people resulting from COVID in each state. As seen from the chart, The state that has the most COVID deaths per 100,000 people is Mississippi. Mississippi has about 472.6836 deaths per 100,000 people. The state that has the least amount of COVID deaths per 100,000 people is Alaska. Alaska has about 50.67301 deaths per 100,000 people. With these observations, states with larger populations located in the southern region of the US have more COVID deaths, opposed to states with smaller populations located elsewhere in the US.

Chart 2

The use of these graphs is to calculate the mask usage proportions in the US by peoples frequency of wearing masks from never, rarely, sometimes, frequently and always. Survey results were averaged and compiled into their respective categories. Roughly 72% of people wore a mask frequently or always during the COVID-19 pandemic.

Chart 3

The scatter plot matrix above depicts all the correlations between variables relating to COVID-19 and the 2020 US elections. Each point represents a state. When the percentage of votes for Biden and Trump were plotted against COVID deaths per 100,000, there was a negative correlation with Biden and a positive correlation with Trump. Several similar trends could be noticed with mask usage and vaccine hesitancy. Additionally, vaccine hesitancy and low mask usage both had positive correlations with deaths per 100,000. This is indicative of how rhetoric from the 2020 presidential candidates influenced people to react differently. The scatter plot matrix depicts how states that Trump won with larger margins had less mask usage and increase vaccine hesitancy. Consequently, higher death rates of COVID were reported in those states.
